T1  - Negotiated Trade Restrictions with Private Political Pressure*
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/11/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937965
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 106
IS  - 4
SP  - 1287
EP  - 1307
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We consider a home government with political pressure to restrict trade. The foreign country is compensated with a portion of the tariff revenues or quota rents, but cannot directly observe the political pressure abroad. In this setting, the two countries negotiate over the volume of trade and transfer of rents, depending on the level of political pressure. We determine globally optimal, incentive-compatible trade policies, in which the home government has no incentive to overstate (or understate) the pressure for protection.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937965
ER  - 



