T1  - Loss Aversion in Riskless Choice: A Reference-Dependent Model*
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/11/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937956
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 106
IS  - 4
SP  - 1039
EP  - 1061
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Much experimental evidence indicates that choice depends on the status quo or reference level: changes of reference point often lead to reversals of preference. We present a reference-dependent theory of consumer choice, which explains such effects by a deformation of indifference curves about the reference point. The central assumption of the theory is that losses and disadvantages have greater impact on preferences than gains and advantages. Implications of loss aversion for economic behavior are considered.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937956
ER  - 



